In this project I chose to try my best at detecting pneumonia in chest X-RAY images.¶

The main method involves using transfer learning from various different kernels already trained on 'imagenet', while trying to keep their bottom layers that have very general and broad features static and train the top level layers.¶

In the end we take all of these models and ensemble them into one prediction model in hope to get the most accurate result.¶

In [7]:
from keras_preprocessing.image_dev import ImageDataGenerator as myImageDataGenerator

Fitting the CNN to the images¶

I modified 'ImageDataGenerator' to include 'keep_aspect_ratio' in order to keep the images in their original ratios padded by black bars.
Chose not to use flip or mirror as the organs' position does matter and I believe that a real world x-ray would not be flipped.

In [8]:
train_datagen = myImageDataGenerator(rescale = 1./255,
                                   shear_range = 0.05,
                                   zoom_range = 0.1,
                                   rotation_range=10,
                                   width_shift_range=0.05,
                                   height_shift_range=0.05,
                                   fill_mode='constant',
                                   cval=0)

test_datagen = myImageDataGenerator(rescale = 1./255)  #Image normalization.

training_set = train_datagen.flow_from_directory(train_folder,
                                                 target_size = input_shape,
                                                 batch_size = batch_size,
                                                 class_mode = 'binary',
                                                 keep_aspect_ratio=True)

validation_set = test_datagen.flow_from_directory(val_folder,
                                                  target_size=input_shape,
                                                  batch_size=batch_size,
                                                  class_mode='binary',
                                                  keep_aspect_ratio=True)

test_set = test_datagen.flow_from_directory(test_folder,
                                            target_size = input_shape,
                                            batch_size = batch_size,
                                            class_mode = 'binary')

VGG16¶

For VGG16 we lock the bottom block of convolutional layers to maintain the broad and very general features from imagenet intact.
Afterwards we train once more only on our added top fully connected layers to try and fine tune them.

In [11]:
from keras.applications import vgg16
In [17]:
conv_base_vgg16 = vgg16.VGG16(include_top=False,
                        weights="imagenet",
                        input_shape=training_set.image_shape)

In [19]:
model_vgg16 = Sequential()
model_vgg16.add(conv_base_vgg16)
# Flatten the layer
model_vgg16.add(Flatten())

model_vgg16.add(Dense(units = 1024))
model_vgg16.add(Dropout(0.3))
model_vgg16.add(Activation('relu'))
model_vgg16.add(Dense(units = 256))
model_vgg16.add(Dropout(0.3))
model_vgg16.add(Activation('relu'))
model_vgg16.add(Dense(units = 32))

# Fully Connected Layers
model_vgg16.add(Dense(activation = 'sigmoid', units = 1))

DenseNet121¶

Similar to VGG16 we want to train most of the top layers where the more specific features exist.¶

In [98]:
from keras.applications import densenet
In [99]:
conv_base_densenet = densenet.DenseNet121(include_top=False,
                                          weights="imagenet",
                                          input_shape=training_set.image_shape)

Adding the top layers, and as we have only 2 classes (sick and not sick) we use the sigmoid function for the final fully connected layer

In [100]:
# Building the top layers
model_densenet = Sequential()
model_densenet.add(conv_base_densenet)
# Flatten the layer
model_densenet.add(Flatten())

model_densenet.add(Dense(units = 1024))
model_densenet.add(Dropout(0.3))
model_densenet.add(Activation('relu'))
model_densenet.add(Dense(units = 256))
model_densenet.add(Dropout(0.3))
model_densenet.add(Activation('relu'))
model_densenet.add(Dense(units = 32))

# Fully Connected Layers
model_densenet.add(Dense(activation = 'sigmoid', units = 1))

Now to freeze the bottom layers

In [12]:
from keras.models import Model
from keras.layers import Input
from keras.layers import Average

models = [model_densenet, model_vgg16, model_resnet50, model_nasnet, model_inceptionv3]
In [13]:
def ensemble_models(models, model_input):
    # collect outputs of models in a list
    y_models=[model(model_input) for model in models] 
    # averaging outputs
    #y_avg=Average()(y_models)
    y_avg=Average()(y_models)
    # build model from same input and avg output
    model_ens = Model(inputs=model_input, outputs=y_avg, name='ensemble')
    return model_ens
In [14]:
model_input = Input(shape=models[0].input_shape[1:])
model_ens = ensemble_models(models, model_input)

# Given unshuffled test set

def get_recall_precision(model, test_set):
    preds = model.predict_generator(test_set, workers=8)
    y_pred = np.around(preds)
    y_true = test_set.classes
    
    tn, fp, fn, tp = 0, 0, 0, 0

    for index in range(len(y_true)):
        if y_pred[index] == 1 and y_true[index] == 1:
            tp += 1
        if y_pred[index] == 0 and y_true[index] == 0:
            tn += 1
        if y_pred[index] == 0 and y_true[index] == 1:
            fn += 1
        if y_pred[index] == 1 and y_true[index] == 0:
            fp += 1
            
    recall = tp/(tp+fn)
    precision = tp/(tp+fp)
    
    return recall, precision
In [24]:
pred_test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale = 1./255)  #Image normalization.

pred_test_set = pred_test_datagen.flow_from_directory(test_folder,
                                            target_size = input_shape,
                                            batch_size = batch_size,
                                            class_mode = 'binary',
                                            shuffle = False)
